attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Bury in Lancashire (now part of Greater Manchester), or from some other similarly named place. The placename comes from the dative case, <i>byrig</i>, of Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’.","Walloon and French: habitational name from any of several places so named, in Wallonia (Belgium) and Oise (France). The placename is from <i>Buriacum</i>, the name of a Gallo-Roman estate, composed of the personal name <i>Burius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","South German: variant of   Buri  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Buri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Markus, Kurt.","Swiss German and South German: from an Alemannic pet form of the personal name <i>Burkhard</i> (see   Burkhart  ).","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Buro  ."]},{"name":"Burgh","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the ten English places named Burgh in northern England and East Anglia, or the six named Brough in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Westmorland, and Yorkshire. All these are from Old English <i>burg</i>, <i>burh</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘massive earthwork, fortification; manor, borough’. Compare   Bury  . The placename <i>Burgh</i> is pronounced as <i>borough</i>. The surname   Brough   arose equally from places now called Burgh and Brough, and is the more common form of the surname in modern Britain, where it is pronounced <i>bruff</i> or <i>broof</i> (/brʊf/). The Scottish surname was probably brought in from Yorkshire. For the surname in Ireland see   Burke  ."]}]},{"name":"Wife","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, originally a local name for someone from the Kingdom (now region) of Fife, which is said to get its name from the legendary Pictish hero <i>Fib</i>, one of the seven sons of Cruithne."],"variants":[{"name":"Fyfe","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Fife ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Wife of Adam de Bury had at least 3 sons with Sir Adam de Bury."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1180–1275":"1180–1275","1195–1220":"1195–1220","1198–1246":"1198–1246","1220–1281":"1220–1281","–Female":"Surnud","ABT 1198":"umbes 1198","1246":"1246","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1195":"1195","abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1281":"1281","1180":"1180","Bury, Lancashire, England":"Bury, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Withnall, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1180–1275":"1180–1275","1195–1220":"1195–1220","1198–1246":"1198–1246","1220–1281":"1220–1281","–Female":"Kuollut","ABT 1198":"noin 1198","1246":"1246","1198":"1198","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1195":"1195","abt 1220":"noin 1220","1281":"1281","1180":"1180","Bury, Lancashire, England":"Bury, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Withnall, Lancashire, Englan